comments.body:
Maybe could:
```c++
std::optional<std::string> LineReader::ReadLine()
{
    if (it == end) return std::nullopt;

    // Limit search to max_read bytes
    const auto limit = std::distance(it, end) > static_cast<long>(max_read) ? std::next(it, max_read) : end;
    const auto line = std::find(it, limit, std::byte{'\n'});

    if (line == limit) {
        if (limit != end) // scanned max_read bytes without line
            throw std::runtime_error("max_read exceeded by LineReader");
        return std::nullopt; // reached end of buffer without line
    }

    const std::string_view untrimmed{
        reinterpret_cast<const char*>(std::to_address(it)),
        static_cast<size_t>(std::distance(it, line) + 1)
    };

    it = std::next(line); // advance iterator
    return std::string(TrimStringView(untrimmed));
}
```

The only change from your code is that this version has a hard limit on `max_read`. Which in my view is much simpler to reason about. The `max_read + 1` retrieval when the "past the limit char" is `\n` seems confusing to me. In networking code, the usual convention is to stop at a fixed size, without caring about what comes next.

